This research objective aims to comprehensively characterize the immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment (TME) of brain metastases (BMs) in melanoma, with a specific focus on identifying novel targets for immunotherapeutic intervention. The central hypothesis is that a detailed understanding of the temporal dynamics, cell-cell interactions, and spatial distribution of immune cells within the BM TME will reveal critical checkpoints and pathways that can be modulated to enhance anti-tumor immune responses. To achieve this, we will utilize advanced single-cell technologies, including Zman-seq for temporal tracking of immune cell infiltration, PIC-seq to study cell-cell interactions, and Stereo-seq for spatial transcriptomics. These technologies will be applied to both orthotopic immunocompetent murine models of melanoma BMs and patient-derived clinical samples. Specifically, we aim to develop integrated tissue models from single-cell data, inferring cellular physiology and potential drug responses through machine learning based analysis. We expect to identify specific cellular trajectories that lead to immune dysfunction, such as the transition of cytotoxic NK cells to impaired states and the differentiation of monocytes into immunosuppressive tumor-associated macrophages (TAMs). The temporal analysis will be crucial to define the time scales over which these transitions occur and the molecular circuits involved. Furthermore, the study will uncover key ligand-receptor interactions and spatial relationships that contribute to immune evasion in the BM TME. A particular focus will be placed on characterizing the role of myeloid checkpoints, such as Trem2, in driving the differentiation of monocytes into immunosuppressive TAMs. Ultimately, the expected results of this objective will include a comprehensive single-cell atlas of the BM TME, detailed differentiation trajectories of immune cells, and a prioritized list of targets for antibody and cytokine-based immunotherapies. These findings will be crucial for developing novel approaches that convert the immunosuppressive BM TME into an immunologically "hot" environment, thereby improving the efficacy of cancer immunotherapies.
